A foundational Dzogchen practice inspired by Garab Dorje’s teachings is to simply rest in awareness without altering or controlling experience. In practice, one might sit in a relaxed posture and, instead of focusing on a specific object, gently recognize the awareness that is already present—the knowing quality of mind itself. When thoughts or sensations arise, instead of following or suppressing them, one allows them to dissolve naturally while remaining in this open, spacious awareness. A simple code-like analogy in Python could be represented as:

python
def rest_in_awareness():
    while True:
        if thought_arises():
            allow_to_dissolve()
        else:
            rest_in_natural_state()

This metaphor highlights the non-interfering, effortless nature of the practice.
